What does the following program print?

```cpp
#include <iostream>
constexpr int cube(int x) { return x * x * x; }
int main() {
    constexpr int a = cube(3);
    int b = cube(4);
    std::cout << a << " " << b << "\n";
}
```

The programmer wants `half` to be a compile-time constant equal to 10. What is wrong?

```cpp
constexpr int halve(int x) { return x / 2; }
int main() {
    int n = 20;
    constexpr int half = halve(n);
}
```

What does this program print?

```cpp
#include <iostream>
constexpr int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
int main() {
    constexpr int x = add(add(1, 2), add(3, 4));
    std::cout << x << "\n";
}
```

A `constexpr` function result can be used as an array size. Why does the following compile successfully?

```cpp
constexpr int size() { return 8; }
int main() {
    int arr[size()];
}
```
